Trump told Comey he wanted his "loyalty," expressed his hopes that Comey could "see his way to letting Flynn go," asked Comey to "lift the cloud" of the Russia investigation over his dealmaking before firing him. For the question of "what was Trump's intent?" behind these actions and others, Comey and Trump give very different interpretations--never mind that they can't even agree on the facts.


Trump's story:


Trump decided to fire Comey upon a "very strong recommendation" from Rosenstein and the Attorney General, but also was going to fire him anyway. Trump is aware of the bad-optics of firing Comey [1][2] due to the Russia investigation, but Trump figured the whole Russia story is just a made-up excuse by sour Democrats [3]. Trump realized that firing Comey might make the Russia investigation take longer, but he had to do the right thing for the American people [4]. Besides, the investigation was just an excuse that should have been over with a long time ago [2], and he wanted the investigation to be sped-up anyway [5].

Other than the DOJ's recommendation, Trump has a long list of reason to fire Comey. For one, Comey is a show-boater and grandstander [6] who had put the FBI in turmoil [7] and bruised public trust in the FBI [8]. Comey did a poor job at the May 3rd Senate Intelligence Committee Hearing, and this is probably why the DOJ wrote their letter [9]. Comey made misstatements during this testimony which the FBI had to correct, which rarely happens [10]. Trump cherishes the FBI and understands they are very special, but because of what happened to the Clinton campaign (and even to Trump's much more successful campaign), the FBI lost that special reputation during the 2016 election [11]. When Trump fired him, Comey was very unpopular, and both Democrats and Republicans were saying terrible things about him [12]. On top of that, Comey is an Obama appointee, and is not Trump's man [13]. In the end, Trump wants someone who's capable and can be a great FBI director, and that's just not Comey [14]. He's the wrong man for that position, and the wrong man for the American people [15]. 

Trump wants the Russia investigation to be absolutely done properly [16]. Neither Trump nor anybody else from the White House asked Comey to drop the Russia investigation [17], and Trump doesn't know of any surrogates who asked on behalf of the White House [18]. Trump wants the investigation to be good and strong, so we can get to the bottom of this [19], but he maintains that the Russia investigation was a set-up by the Democrats [20]. Trump says there is no collusion between his campaign and the Russians, and the Russians did not affect the vote [21]. Besides the Miss Universe pageant in Moscow and selling a home to a wealthy Russian, Trump himself has nothing to do with Russia [22].

Trump did not urge Comey in any way to back down the investigation into Micheal Flynn [23]. Trump was aware of Yate's warning about Flynn, but he didn't think it was that big of a deal. Trump says the White House Counsel, Don McGahn, didn't make the problems with Flynn sound like any kind of emergency or anything urgent, and neither did Yates in her Congressional hearing [24]. Trump thought it would be unfair to immediately fire Flynn, a General and a good person, after hearing from somebody he doesn't even know [25]. But ultimately, Trump fired Flynn because he lied to the Vice President [26].

Comey asked Trump to meet at the Jan 27th dinner because Comey wanted to keep his job. [27] This was the first time Comey told Trump he is not under investigation [28]. Trump never asked Comey for his loyalty [29], and did not feel that Comey contradicting his wiretapping claims was a sign of disloyalty [30].

Trump was surprised when Comey publicly declared there was no evidence for his wiretapping claims, but he wasn't angry [31]. Nor was Trump angry when Comey revealed the FBI was investigating his campaign for colluding with Russia. In fact, newspaper stories saying Trump was angry might have used false sources, or even sources that don't exist [32].

Trump never thought about the optics of firing Comey the day before meeting with Lavrov, because creating jobs, strength, security, and strong borders are more important than optics [33]. The meeting was a public meeting, and very public since Trump announced it and everybody knew about it [34]. Putin asked Trump to set up the meeting [35].


