Comey's story:


Comey was confused by Trump's shifting explanations on why he was fired. Trump repeatedly told Comey he was doing a great job, heard great things about him from the Attorney General and others, and hoped he would stay as Director [1]. Trump was lying when he said Comey was a poor leader of the FBI and that the FBI was in disarray and had lost confidence in Comey [2].

At first, Comey didn't know that Trump fired him because of the Russia investigation, but after watching his interview with Lester Holt, Comey saw that Trump said he fired him because of the Russia investigation, and Comey takes him at his word [3][4]. Trump fired Comey to change how the investigation was being conducted [5][6].

Other than media reports, Comey is not aware of any attempts by Trump to reach out to Admiral Rogers, DNI Coats, or DCI Pompeo to publicly exonerate Trump or intervene with the FBI regarding the FBI's investigation [7].

Comey first met Trump on Janurary 6th, when he briefed Trump on the "dodgy dossier." Part of the reason to brief Trump on the dossier was that Trump might be being blackmailed by the Russians [8]. During this briefing, Comey let Trump know he was not under investigation [9].

Trump called Comey on March 30 and described the Russia investigation as a "cloud" that was impairing his ability to act on behalf of the country [10]. Comey interpreted Trump as saying the investigation was draining his time and energy and making it harder for him to focus on other priorities [11]. Trump expressed to Comey that he had nothing to do with Russia and wanted the FBI to do the Russia investigation and get all the facts out. Trump specifically asked Comey to get out that he personally was not under investigation [12], and expressed that it would be good to find out if his surrogates did something wrong or clear their names too [13].

Immediately after this, Trump turned the conversation to FBI Deputy Director McCabe and mentioned he hadn't brought up "the McCabe thing" because Comey said McCabe was honorable, even though McCabe had accepted Campaign donations from the Clintons under suspicious circumstances [14]. Trump said he was rough on McCabe on the campaign trail, and asked Comey how McCabe was going to be with Trump as President [15]. Trump finished the call by emphasizing his problems with "the cloud" and expressing his hopes Comey could find a way to make public Trump wasn't being investigated. Comey told Trump he'd see what we can do [16][17]. Comey did not tell Trump that the FBI and DOJ didn't want to publicly reveal Trump was not under investigation, in part because that would create a duty to correct if that changed [18][19].

Trump asked Comey "lift the cloud" during the March 30 call and complained about the "cloud" again during an April 11th phone call. Comey interpreted "the cloud" to mean the Russia investigation in general [20], and Comey understood Trump to be requesting that the Russia investigation be dropped [21]. The March 30 phone call was the third time Comey let Trump know he was not under investigation [22].

Comey thinks he told Trump he was not under investigation during the April 11th call too [23]. During that call, Trump wanted to know what Comey had done about his request to make public that Trump was not under investigation [24]. Trump tried to remind Comey that he had "been very loyal to you, very loyal; we had that thing you know." Comey was curious what Trump meant by "that thing" but didn't ask him [25]. At the end of the call, Comey told Trump to take his request to Boente and Trump agreed [26].

There have been lots of news stories about the Russia investigation and collusion that get the facts wrong [27]. Specifically, one could characterize the February 14th New York Times story "Trump campaign aides had repeated contacts with Russian intelligence" as "almost entirely wrong." [28] The story alleged extensive electronic surveillance, and that upset Comey so much that he surveyed the intelligence community to see if he was missing something. Comey sought out Republican and Democrat Senators to let them know the story had factual errors [29].

Comey believes Trump asked him to drop the investigation into Flynn [30]. When Trump asked Comey to "let Flynn go" at the February 14th Oval Office meeting, Comey perceived this as an order [31][32]. If Comey did what Trump wanted, he would have dropped any open criminal investigation into Flynn's contacts with the Russians [33]. Comey believes it is unlikely that closing the investigation into Flynn would have impeded the Russia investigation [34].

Comey did not in any way initiate the Jan 27th dinner meeting with Trump [35], and Trump was not describing the situation accurately when he said Comey "wanted to have dinner because he wanted to stay on" [32]. Trump began the dinner by asking if Comey wanted to stay as FBI director, then asked Comey for loyalty specifically in the context of asking him to stay. Trump had already asked Comey to stay three times, and Comey saw Trump's request for loyalty as a way to get something in exchange for letting Comey keep his job and create a patronage relationship [36]. At the end of the dinner, Trump asked Comey for "honest loyalty, and Comey went along with it [37][38].

During the dinner, Trump reacted strongly to the "dodgy dossier" and told Comey he was tempted to order him to investigate it. The January 27th dinner was the second time Comey told Trump he was not under investigation [39], and Trump did not ask Comey to back off the Flynn investigation at the dinner [40].


1. http://www.politico.com/story/2017/06/08/full-text-james-comey-trump-russia-testimony-239295
But then the explanations, the shifting explanations, confused me and increasingly concerned me. They confused me because the president and I had had multiple conversations about my job, both before and after he took office, and he had repeatedly told me I was doing a great job, and he hoped I would stay. And I had repeatedly assured him that I did intend to stay and serve out the years of my term. He told me repeatedly that he had talked to lots of people about me, including our current Attorney General, and had learned that I was doing a great job, and that I was extremely well-liked by the FBI workforce. 


2. http://www.politico.com/story/2017/06/08/full-text-james-comey-trump-russia-testimony-239295
And although the law required no reason at all to fire an FBI director, the administration then chose to defame me and more importantly the FBI by saying that the organization was in disarray, that it was poorly led, that the workforce had lost confidence in its leader. Those were lies, plain and simple.


3. http://www.politico.com/story/2017/06/08/full-text-james-comey-trump-russia-testimony-239295
SEN. DIANNE FEINSTEIN: Thanks very much, Mr. Chairman. Mr. Comey, I just want you to know that I have great respect for you. Senator Cornyn and I sit on the judiciary committee and we have the occasion to have you before us. You're a man of strength and I regret the situations we all find ourselves in. I just want to say that. Let me begin with one overarching question. Why do you believe you were fired?

COMEY: I guess I don't know for sure. I believe — I think the president, at his word, that I was fired because of the Russia investigation. Something about the way I was conducting it, the president felt created pressure on him that he wanted to relieve. Again, I didn't know that at the time. I watched his interview. I read the press accounts of his conversations. I take him at his word there. Look, I could be wrong. Maybe he's saying something that's not true. I take him at his word, at least based on what I know now. 


4. http://www.politico.com/story/2017/06/08/full-text-james-comey-trump-russia-testimony-239295
So it confused me when I saw on television the president saying that he actually fired me because of the Russia investigation, and learned again from the media that he was telling privately other parties that my firing had relieved great pressure on the Russian investigation.


