While they might be right with on that point, overall neither of their stories completely hold up.

Trump says Rosenstein wrote his memo on Comey because of Comey's poor performance in Congressional hearings, and Trump describes his reason to fire Comey as "accepting the recommendation" of Rosenstein and Sessions. But Trump was planning to fire Comey before that, and Trump asked Rosenstein for the memo:


http://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/read-rosensteins-full-opening-statement-comey-congress/
	On May 8, I learned that President Trump intended to remove Director Comey and sought my advice and input. Notwithstanding my personal affection for Director Comey, I thought it was appropriate to seek a new leader.

	I wrote a brief memorandum to the Attorney General summarizing my longstanding concerns about Director Comey’s public statements concerning the Secretary Clinton email investigation.

	I chose the issues to include in my memorandum. 

	...I sent my signed memorandum to the Attorney General after noon on Tuesday, May 9.


It looks like Trump was trying to hide his reasons for firing Comey.

Trump claims he "cherishes" the FBI, but it looks like Trump only likes the FBI when he thinks they're doing him favors:


https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/10/28/trump-says-fbi-letter-means-system-might-not-rigged-thought/WND8gcgRPAJDXd0EBerPaI/story.html
